<subSubSection id="6C85E900A6294F7917921BB57BF5A30B" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="185BA6FF2816CBC5E4476D0283D66FA5" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F8421E135CC7E7DDF3CAD7045684A52A" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
This species is easy to recognise by the short apical lobes on the 10th tergite of the male and cerci clearly upcurved and with a lateral spine. The most closely-related species is 
<taxonomicName id="8A35F95BEF2E8913828E30C5C4A865D5" class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. africana" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="africana">
<emphasis id="47D9C0EA58FD715480A21FFB300E03CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. africana</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which, however, has much longer lobes of the 10th abdominal tergite and more robust cerci.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="2CED2C922BCB9D76D904032ADEE55D99" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="description">
<paragraph id="B57CAAE1B7F2E40CB7C064FC99E6A4D1" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="22993F3162822243F306B0556E783E7A" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
Typical 
<taxonomicName id="A5DD24030B400AE683410AB93B354F87" authorityName="Brunner von Wattenwyl" authorityYear="1878" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poreuomena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Poreuomena" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="81988CA724DFD96F751EDD7E82BC8344" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Poreuomena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with narrow tegmina surpassed by the alae by a few mm (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E4DF4DA3C6893F29FCB3BAE9B970A659" captionStart="Figures 62–64" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 62 - 64. Morphological details of male Poreuomena huxleyi. Habitus (62), lateral view on apex (63), stridulatory area (64)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures62-64" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499191" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">62</figureCitation>
). Stridulatory area marked brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="98EF8E3A16DD2BFF6510F06B1B4ECAB6" captionStart="Figures 62–64" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 62 - 64. Morphological details of male Poreuomena huxleyi. Habitus (62), lateral view on apex (63), stridulatory area (64)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures62-64" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499191" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">64</figureCitation>
). Two spines are present on the ventral margin of the hind femora. The apical lobes of the 10th tergite are short and square, separated widely (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="4B4054E1D5C0160BE6D0814B64A994DB" captionStart="Figures 62–64" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figures 62 - 64. Morphological details of male Poreuomena huxleyi. Habitus (62), lateral view on apex (63), stridulatory area (64)." figureDoi="10.3897/dez.68.60193.figures62-64" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/499191" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">63</figureCitation>
); the cerci are in- and downcurved, dorso-ventrally flattened in the apical portion where a lateral spine is present.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="6668B88991BA7B787B5A988792CB2683" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" type="colour">
<paragraph id="049A1798884A5AC5E0478A04A49C45F2" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">Colour.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6AFCF31C2A69F98368741141B3D4E103" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">
<taxonomicName id="8B5F543F2A1E5C15303C85FFA4BF04D2" class="Insecta" genus="P." higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="P. huxleyi" order="Orthoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="45" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="huxleyi">
<emphasis id="598379B670CEE126208DD25758B50AAF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="45">P. huxleyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is brownish coloured, with green tegmina and hind tibiae; a black marking is typical at the base of the tegmina and some small black spots on the posterior margin of the tegmina.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
